on was an obvious NOOP.\n\nClean workspaces -- everything else, including `evals/clients`, `runtime`, `relay`, `mcp`, `models`, `signal-core`, `daemon-client`, `updater`, `test-scenarios`, and the various admin/desktop adapters -- pick up the rule via the preset and now block any new file-level disables.\n\n### Edge cases handled\n\n- `// eslint-disable-line <rule>` and `// eslint-disable-next-line <rule>`: never reported (these are line-scoped directives, not block comments).\n- `{/* eslint-disable-next-line rule */}` inside JSX: not reported -- it's a per-line directive that happens to use block-comment syntax.\n- Paired `/* eslint-disable */ ... /* eslint-enable */` regions: not reported.\n- A block-comment-shaped string literal containing the text `eslint-disable`: not reported (ESLint's parser doesn't see strings as comments).\n- Self-suppression: ESLint's directive processor would normally swallow our own `context.report` for the very `/* eslint-disable */` we're trying to flag (the disable disables our rule too). We bypass that the same way `eslint-plugin-eslint-comments/no-unlimited-disable` does -- by reporting at column `-1` so the directive's range filter never matches the report location.\n\n### Test coverage\n\n16 RuleTester cases (9 valid / 7 invalid):\n- valid: line disables, paired block disables, JSDoc / regular block comments, JSX block-comment `eslint-disable-next-line`, `eslint-disable` inside a string literal.\n- invalid: file-level `/* eslint-disable */`, single-rule and multi-rule listings, `--` description form, mid-file disable with no paired enable, two stacked file-level disables, mismatched pairing where the enable lists a different rule than the disable.\n\n## Related Issue\n\nCloses PLT-76\n\n## Potential Risk & Impact\n\n- **Behavior NOOP for existing code.** Workspaces with existing violations have the rule explicitly turned off; their lint output and runtime behavior are unchanged. Workspaces with no existing violations get the rule 